{"questionId":"14678744","questionHtml":"<p>Hence, show that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;are solutions of the equation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>factorising&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>5</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>5</mn><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>16</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>5</mn><mfenced><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>5</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;</strong></em>and<em><strong>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>5</mn><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>The<em><strong>&nbsp;R1&nbsp;</strong></em>is independent of the<strong><em>&nbsp;M1</em></strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>solving&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>5</mn><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>The<strong>&nbsp;<em>R1</em>&nbsp;</strong>is independent of the<strong>&nbsp;<em>M1</em>.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p>therefore either&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>≠</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>≠</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;(or only solution to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>therefore&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;are solutions of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>The final<strong>&nbsp;<em>R1</em>&nbsp;</strong>is dependent on both previous marks.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\">&nbsp;<em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"14678744","referenceCode":"23N.1.AHL.TZ1.12ci","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, show that θ=π5 and θ=3π5 are solutions of the equation 16 sin4θ-20 sin2θ+5=0.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.12—Factor and remainder theorems, sum and product of roots","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.13—Polar and Euler form","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.14—Complex roots of polynomials, conjugate roots, De Moivre’s, powers & roots of complex numbers"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}